<paragraph id="8B8436D8FFC82A36FF71FAB4FD64FA15" blockId="12.[160,658,1406,1430]" box="[160,658,1406,1430]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">
<typeStatus id="5480887AFFC82A36FF71FAB4FF20FA15" box="[160,214,1406,1430]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFC82A36FEEEFAB4FD64FA15" authority="Karny." box="[319,658,1406,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Dolichothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicollis">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFC82A36FEEEFAB4FDB5FA15" box="[319,579,1406,1430]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Dolichothrips longicollis</emphasis>
Karny.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8436D8FFC82A37FF71FA71FD45F908" blockId="12.[160,1156,1467,1699]" lastBlockId="13.[160,1155,1513,1675]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="1401" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">
<materialsCitation id="3B533C85FFC82A36FF71FA71FBB6FA50" box="[160,1088,1467,1491]" collectorName="This" location="south Asia" municipality="ThripsWiki" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<collectorName id="26CE530EFFC82A36FF71FA71FF3BFA50" box="[160,205,1467,1491]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">This</collectorName>
genus comprises about 20 species, mostly from 
<location id="8EE46003FFC82A36FD2CFA71FC85FA50" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:039287CEFFC82A37FDC7FA83FD45F908:8EE46003FFC82A36FD2CFA71FC85FA50" box="[765,883,1467,1491]" municipality="ThripsWiki" name="south Asia" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">south Asia</location>
(
<collectingMunicipality id="6BE0ACA2FFC82A36FC53FA71FC0EFA50" box="[898,1016,1467,1491]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">ThripsWiki</collectingMunicipality>
2015)
</materialsCitation>
. They are all presumably phytophagous, feeding in flowers and buds (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFC82A36FC73FA14FF21F99B" author="Mound LA &amp; Minaei K" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" pagination="2919 - 2978" refId="ref9815" refString="Mound LA, Minaei K. 2007. Australian thrips of the Haplothrips lineage (Insecta: Thysanoptera). J Nat Hist. 41: 2919 - 2978." type="journal article" year="2007">Mound and Minaei 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Almost all of the species bear three sense cones on antennal segment III and four on IV, and the mouth cone is unusually long and pointed, extending between the fore coxae (
<figureCitation id="13002A5DFFC82A36FEFDF98CFE6BF9DD" box="[300,413,1606,1630]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1431,1454]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1400]" captionTargetId="figure-43@9.[163,1153,142,1400]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 1. Haplothripini species of Central and South America. (A) Dolichothrips indicus, head. (B) Bagnalliella yuccae, head and pronotum. (C) Androthrips ramachandrai, fore leg with tubercle near base (arrow). (D) Podothrips bambusae, mouth cone and prosternum. (E) Podothrips bambusae, fore leg. (F) Leptothrips mali, head. (G) Leptothrips mali, metanotum. (H) Karnyothrips flavipes, antenna. (I) Karnyothrips flavipes, metanotum with only one pair of setae (arrows). (J) Karnyothrips flavipes, tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206280" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206280/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
). 
<materialsCitation id="3B533C85FFC82A36FE67F98CFB89F9DD" box="[438,1151,1606,1630]" collectorName="The" location="Asian" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<collectorName id="26CE530EFFC82A36FE67F98CFE29F9DD" box="[438,479,1606,1630]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">The</collectorName>
only species recorded from the Americas is the 
<location id="8EE46003FFC82A36FBF5F98CFB97F9DD" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:039287CEFFC82A37FDC7FA83FD45F908:8EE46003FFC82A36FBF5F98CFB97F9DD" box="[1060,1121,1606,1630]" name="Asian" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Asian</location>
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFC82A36FBBDF98CFB89F9DD" baseAuthorityName="Hood" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1132,1151,1606,1630]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Dolichothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFC82A36FBBDF98CFB89F9DD" box="[1132,1151,1606,1630]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">D</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</materialsCitation>
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFC82A36FB51F98CFF1AF903" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">. indicus</emphasis>
, which was collected in pepper and eggplants in 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7648FFC82A36FCE7F9A2FC4CF903" box="[822,954,1640,1664]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFC82A36FC1BF9A2FF21F920" author="Cabrera-Asencio I" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" pagination="111 - 112" refId="ref9010" refString="Cabrera-Asencio I. 1998. Dolichothrips indicus Hood Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae: a new report from peppers and eggplants in Puerto Rico. J Agric Univ P R. 82: 111 - 112." type="journal article" year="1998">Cabrera-Asencio 1998</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFC82A36FF3FF941FE82F920" author="Lima EFB" box="[238,372,1675,1699]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" refId="ref9591" refString="Lima EFB. 2011. Thrips (Insecta: Thysanoptera) associated with Fabaceae species in the Brazilian Mid-North [dissertation]. Piracicaba: ESALQ. Portuguese." type="book" year="2011">Lima (2011)</bibRefCitation>
referred this species living in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFC82A36FD05F941FCEAF920" box="[724,796,1675,1699]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFC82A36FD05F941FCEAF920" box="[724,796,1675,1699]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Acacia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flowers in north-eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7648FFC82A36FB93F941FB77F920" box="[1090,1153,1675,1699]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="1400">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<materialsCitation id="3B533C85FFC92A37FF71FA23FC3EF9C5" collectorName="This &amp; New World" country="Barbados" location="Susan Broda" municipality="Laurence Mound" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<collectorName id="26CE530EFFC92A37FF71FA23FF3BF982" box="[160,205,1513,1537]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">This</collectorName>
species has been shown to have spread to the 
<collectorName id="26CE530EFFC92A37FCF8FA23FC5AF982" box="[809,940,1513,1537]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">New World</collectorName>
tropics, including 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7648FFC92A37FF71F9C1FEFDF9A0" box="[160,267,1547,1571]" name="Barbados" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">Barbados</collectingCountry>
, Trinidad and Florida (
<location id="8EE46003FFC92A37FDFEF9C1FD31F9A0" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:039287CEFFC82A37FDC7FA83FD45F908:8EE46003FFC92A37FDFEF9C1FD31F9A0" box="[559,711,1547,1571]" country="Barbados" municipality="Laurence Mound" name="Susan Broda" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">Susan Broda</location>
and 
<collectingMunicipality id="6BE0ACA2FFC92A37FCC7F9C1FC17F9A0" box="[790,993,1547,1571]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">Laurence Mound</collectingMunicipality>
, unpublished records), and is often associated with plants of the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFC92A37FC9EF9E4FC3EF9C5" box="[847,968,1582,1606]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malvaceae</taxonomicName>
</materialsCitation>
. Apart from the long mouth cone, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFC92A37FEBEF99BFE2EF9EA" baseAuthorityName="Hood" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[367,472,1617,1641]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Dolichothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFC92A37FEBEF99BFE2EF9EA" box="[367,472,1617,1641]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1401">D. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristic in exhibiting basantra longer than wide, and mesopresternum forming two lateral triangles.
</paragraph>
